03916nam a22005535i 9780271092720DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710927207 a10.1515/97802710927202doi  a(DE-B1597)590487  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0400402bisacsh1 aBerger, Pamela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHebrew Psalms and the Utrecht Psalter :bVeiled Origins /cPamela Berger. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b38 color/52 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Methodology and the Example of Psalm 1 -- t2 Analysis of the Pictorial Motifs in Selected Utrecht Psalter Illustrations -- t3 Late Antique Galilee: The Context for the Creation of the Model for the Utrecht Psalter Illustrations -- t4 The Style of the Utrecht Psalter and Its Relation to Late Antique Jewish Art -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a major departure from previous scholarship, this volume argues that the illustrations in the famous and widely influential Utrecht Psalter manuscript were inspired by a late antique Hebrew version of Psalms, rather than a Latin, Christian version of the text.Produced during the early ninth century in a workshop near Reims, France, the Utrecht Psalter is illustrated with pen-and-ink drawings in a lively style reminiscent of Hellenistic art. The motifs are largely literal renditions of words and phrases found in the book of Psalms. However, more than three dozen motifs cannot be explained by either the Latin text that accompanies the imagery or the commentaries of the church fathers. Through a close reading of the Hebrew Psalms, Pamela Berger demonstrates that these motifs can be explained only by the Hebrew text, the Jewish commentary, or Jewish art. Drawing comparisons between the "Hellenistic" style of the Psalter images and the style of late antique Galilean mosaics and using evidence from recent archaeological discoveries, Berger argues that the model for those Psalter illustrations dependent on the Hebrew text was produced in the Galilee.Pioneering and highly persuasive, this book resolves outstanding issues surrounding the origins of one of the most extensively studied illuminated manuscripts. It will be mandatory reading for many historians of medieval art and literature and for those interested in the Hebrew text of the book of Psalms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Sacred Writings.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271092720zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271092720423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271092720.jpg  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK